For the detection of puerarin in human plasma, the human plasma in 0°C was firstly centrifuged at 18,000rpm for 20min, and the supernatant was used as the disperse medium. Under the exact same experimental conditions, a similar linear relationship between Ipa and c is given as Ipa (μA)=–4.188c (μmolL−1) +0.025 (R=0.9997) in the concentration range of 4–0.05μmolL−1 with the sensitivity of 59.28μAμmolL−1
                        cm−2 and the detection limit (S/N=3) of 10nmolL−1(Fig. 5B and Table 2). Three amounts of puerarin were added into human plasma, and the measured recoveries ranged from 95.6% to 100.3% with the relative standard deviation (RSD) less than 8% (Table 3
                        ), giving the satisfactory results in determination of puerarin in complex biological samples.
